snippet.textDisplay: So an opportunity popped up with a really good find, so I went and bought it for $500!!! This really shows you what you can do to find your first project car, find a budget suv, etc with minimal risk and a lot of potential reward!!! snippet.textDisplay: That method for checking fuses with a multi meter is incorrect.  Fuses can fail leaving a very small connection which will show ohms on a multimeter but is too small of a connection to pass any amperage.  Fuses can look good but have high resistance.  Fuses should show less then 1 ohm of resistance.  Do not open the sunroof, if you do it will break since it is a very common failure point.  I have rebuilt them before.  You need to remove the 4 screws from the inside and remove the glass panel so you can clean and lubricate the tracks and lift cams.
snippet.textOriginal: That method for checking fuses with a multi meter is incorrect.  Fuses can fail leaving a very small connection which will show ohms on a multimeter but is too small of a connection to pass any amperage.  Fuses can look good but have high resistance.  Fuses should show less then 1 ohm of resistance.  Do not open the sunroof, if you do it will break since it is a very common failure point.  I have rebuilt them before. Usually can’t fault your methods of working but using Ohms to check for blown fuse in an intact circuit isn’t ideal as the voltage used to test for an complete or broken circuit has the potential to fry modules connected to the circuit.

Better off using voltage drop either side of the fuse

snippet.textDisplay:
That exhaust clamp will do almost nothing. It can't crimp down on the new exhaust like that, it will not hold like that. You have to use an angle grinder and make a little cut in it.

Also, you always check the oil of an automatic transmission with a running engine. In park or neutral depending which car. You can see that information on the dipstick.
